<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="2ff3ce81-c48a-5002-924c-d6d6034278c1" activityNameId="bc00ceb6-2ae3-4771-b9f4-60ef3394931a" parentActivityId="fa2c2207-3fe8-4781-8a2a-fd9eafc550d0" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1" energyValues="0">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">phenyl acetic acid production</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">C8H8O2</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en"/>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">production of phenyl acetic acid including materials, energy uses, infrastructure, and emissions</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The process “phenyl acetic acid, at plant, GLO" is modelled for the production of phenyl acetic acid from benzyl chloride. Raw materials are modelled with a stoechiometric calculation. Emissions are estimated. Energy consumptions, infrastructure and transports are calculated with standard values.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Phenylacetic acid (C6H5CH2CO2H; CAS 103-82-2) forms white leaflets on vacuum distillation. It dissolves in hot water but is only slightly soluble in cold water. Hydrolysis of benzyl nitrile or carbonylation of benzyl halides or alcohols produces phenylacetic acid. An example is a carbonylation of benzyl chloride with sodium cyanide followed by a hydrolysis:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">1. C7H7Cl + NaCN → C8H7N + NaCl</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">2. C8H7N + 2 H2O → C8H8O2 + NH3</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Phenylacetic acid is a starting material in the synthesis of synthetic perfumes and cosmetics. It is used in the synthesis of penicillin G to stimulate benzylpenicillinase in E. Coli. Penicillin G, after extraction from the culture, is converted to 6-aminopenicillanic acid and phenylacetic acid.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Frischknecht R., Jungbluth N., Althaus H.-J., Doka G., Dones R., Heck T., Hellweg S., Hischier R., Nemecek T., Rebitzer G. and Spielmann M. (2007) Overview and Methodology. Final report ecoinvent v2.0 No. 1. Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, CH, retrieved from: www.ecoinvent.org.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Gendorf (2000) Umwelterklärung 2000, Werk Gendorf. Werk Gendorf, Burgkirchen as pdf-File under: http://www.gendorf.de/pdf/umwelterklaerung2000.pdf</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10">Hosea Cheung, Robin S. Tanke, G. Paul Torrence: Acetic Acid. Published online: 2000. In: Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Seventh Edition, 2004 Electronic Release (ed. Fiedler E., Grossmann G., Kersebohm D., Weiss G. and Witte C.). 7 th Electronic Release Edition. Wiley InterScience, New York, Online-Version under: DOI: 10.1002/14356007.a01_045</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
